bank, Stefan Leins argues that financial analysts construct stories of possible economic futures, presenting them as coherent and grounded in expert research and analysis. In so doing, they establish a role for themselves-not necessarily by laying bare empirically verifiable trends but rather by presenting the market as something that makes sense and is worth investing in. Stories of Capitalism is a nuanced look at how banks continue to boost investment-even in unstable markets-and a rare insider's look into the often opaque financial practices that shape the global economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aBanks and bankingzSwitzerland. 0aFinancexSocial aspects. 0aFinancial analysts. 0aFinancial services industryxEmployees. 0aInvestment bankingxSocial aspectszSwitzerland. 4aSwiss banking. 4aanthropology of finance. 4aeconomic anthropology. 4aethnography. 4afinancial analysis. 4aforecasting. 4anarratives. 4aneoliberalism. 4aprediction. 4avaluation. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226523569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226523569.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles